definition: IDD / IDE = Integrated development environment
DOM = document object model
HTML = Hyper - text markup language
CSS = Cascading style sheets
Terminal / Command line = A text - based interface to the system
Shell = The part of your operating system that defines how the terminal will behave / look
Bash = Bourne Again SHell
DRY = Don 't repeat yourself
href = Hyper - text reference
User story = the scenario that the hypothetical 'user' wants to see on the page - you have to build it out. Can be detailed or vague.
Alt text = text that displays when the browser can't load the element or for impared users. This text is also a great way to get found in search results.
HTML containers = The commonly used sections that compose your HTML file. Containers help with readability and organization
Attributes = the extra information inside an HTML element that povides additional data.

CSS selectors: Element / class / id = the selector determining which bits of the HTML page will be styled. Element seletcs all of that particular type of element, Class (.) selects all elements with the that class attribute, and ID (#) seletcs only the particular element with that ID listed.
NAN = Not a Number
SDET = Software Design Engineer in Test
SDE = Software Design Engineer
Program = A list of computer instructions that tell a computer what to do.
(GIT) ACP = add commit push
CamelCasing = the standard style of capitalization in JavaScript, where theLaterWordsAreInCaps. because it looks like camelHumps.
Interpolate = insert
Argument = the input, eg the 9 in multiply(9)
Parameter = variables in a function name that recieve an input
Function declaration = a function that is bound to an identifier or name
Modulous operator = % , finds the remainder
Operators = the symbols used to assign values, compare values, perform arithmetic operations, etc.
Lexical order = the numerical value assigned to strings is based off of the first letter.This is the mathematical term for alphabetical order.
Boolean = true and false values
Scope = the degree to which an object is accessible by other functions.Eg.an object within a function is local to that function, where as an object outside of all functions has global scope.
Loops = while loops and for loops let you perform an action multiple times, or only in certain cases.
Itteration = i, the count commonly used in for loops
API = application programing interface
DBMS = data base management system
Front end = “client - side” development, where the focus is on what users see
Open-source = software that is available for public use, change, and improvement
This = specifies the object or variable within that particular scope.changes when called in a different location.
Constructor function = a function that creates a new object
Global = accessable from any location
Local = accessable only within the object
Event listener = 'listens' for a specific event to happen on the web page, which calls the action assigned
Higher order function = functions within functions.some examples are the functions you can add within.filter.map and.reduce
Arity = the number of expected arguments in a function. Eg. function(a, b, c) {} has an arity of .
Regex = regular expression
Dev = developer
PM = project manager
JSX = a syntax extension for JavaScript to be used with React. JSX is not 'real' JavaScript, so it needs to go through a compiler so that the browser will know what to do with it.
Foo / bar / foobar = common placeholder names when the name is temporary or unimportant. Used to help stress the concept or idea rather than the function itself.
The virtual DOM = a virtual copy of the actual DOM which allows React to update only changed objects. it does this by diffing.
Diffing = a change updates the entire virtual DOM, which then is compared to a pre-snapshot. Only changed objects get updated in the real DOM.
Conditionals = expressions that are only executed under certain conditions
Method = we can write methods, and js also includes available methods. Essentially a built-in function / a function built in to an object
Recursion = a function that calls itself as part of the function. Works using built-in stacks.
Json file = a file that contains a set of data. Arranged in an array, commonly with multiple key values.
Preload = loeds data before use to help speed up page loading time.
CDN = content delivery network
Components = small, reusable pieces of code that return a React element to be rendered to the page.
Props = inputs to a component or function. Used to pass data down from a parent to a child.
